Acute respiratory infections are the major health concern after flooding in displaced populations. Reports from south Asia and United States indicate that upper respiratory infections are the most common infectious diseases post flooding. Destruction of homes and overcrowding increases the risk of transmission respiratory viral pathogens. Immersion in flood water or aspiration of contaminated water can inoculate pathogens (often polymicrobial) to lower respiratory tract. Flulike and upper respiratory tract symptoms including cough, sore throat, rhinitis have been frequently observed among refugees due to exposure to allergens or viral pathogens (
 Paterson et al., 2018; 
 Alderman et al., 2012; 
 Baqir et al., 2012). Aspiration of flood water can conduce pneumonia and be worsen with abscess formation, empyema and pulmonary necrosis. After tsunami disaster in 2004 in Sri Lanka, about 30% of displaced people were complaining of respiratory problems which probably related to post aspiration pneumonia (
 Ivers and Ryan, 2006).
